>>21586855
Just jump into the action. Let details slip themselves in afterwards. Or start with a casual observation by one of the characters or conversation something along those lines. That usually greases the gears for me. If you're afraid it sounds too much like a normal city, shake history up a bit. Pollution or craters from an old war riddle the city, making traveling more hazardous or costly
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Thu 28 Feb 2019 13:52:57 No.21588044 Report
Quoted By:
>>21586855
Basically >>21587628 turn exposition into story or situation. For example, instead of: “the rising cost of augmentations and the medicines to keep them working are costly” to explain it, make it: “she frownd at her arm, probably worrying about the upkeep costs of the new life the accident caused.” Instead of telling about the world, try to draw yourself or others into the world as you develop characters or situations. The only time this really starts to fail is when you jump topics too much and just start spoiting sci-fi with no connection.
